http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Early Learning Standards Framework Content Standards and Learning Criteria for West Virginia Pre-Kindergarten

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The West Virginia Early Learning Standards are grounded in scientific research of child development, children's approaches to learning and effective educational practices. Vital to implementing these standards is the ability to teach using appropriate strategies. The foremost goal for West Virginia's children is to be lifelong learners. Young children live in a society where information is constantly changing and the ability to function well in an increasingly global economy is essential. Children must have the ability to continuously learn. Therefore, it is essential that children develop skills which allow them to become competent, independent learners capable of higher intellectual functions. To fulfill this role, teachers of young children must also be lifelong learners, continuously building their professional knowledge and functional competencies based on current research.
Social and Emotional Development
Self-Concept
Development of self-concept
Describe self by using several basic characteristics.
Demonstrates growing confidence in a range of abilities and expresses pride in accomplishments.
Develops growing capacity for independence in a range of activities, routines, and tasks.
Development of self-expression and self-awareness
Demonstrates progress in expressing needs, wants and feelings appropriately.
Acts out roles by imitating typical actions associated with the roles.
Social Relationships
Development and demonstration of pro-social behaviors
Develops positive relationships with children and adults.
Shows empathy and caring for others.
Demonstrates increasing capacity to follow rules and routines and use materials purposefully, safely, and respectfully.
Shows progress in developing and sustaining friendship with peers.
Manages transitions and begins to adapt to change in routines.
Cooperation
Uses appropriate communication skills to initiate or join classroom activities.
Engages in cooperative group play.
Begins to share materials and experiences and take turns.
Uses and accepts negotiation, compromise, and discussion to resolve conflicts.
Accepts guidance and directions from a variety of familiar adults.
Follows basic routines and rules for play and group participation.
Knowledge of Family and Community
Progression of understanding of their role in the family and community
Understands and describes the interactive roles and relationships among family members.
Identifies and describes roles and relationships of community members.
Understands similarities and respects differences among people, such as genders, race, special needs, cultures, language, and family structures.
Identifies themselves as a member of groups within a community.
Identifies and describes locations and places in their environment.
Dispositions to Learning
Intrinsic Motivation for Learning
Participates in a variety of classroom activities and tasks.
Develops increased ability to make independent choices.
Approaches tasks and activities with flexibility, imagination, and inventiveness.
Persists in and completes tasks, activities, projects, and experiences.
Demonstrates increasing ability to set goals and develop and follow through on plans.
Maintains increasing concentration over a reasonable amount of time despite distractions and interruptions.
Language and Literacy
Listening and Speaking
Utilization of receptive and expressive language for a variety of purposes
Demonstrates an increasing ability to attend to and understand communication.
Communicates needs and wants through a variety of verbal and symbolic forms.
Understands and uses increasingly complex and varied vocabulary/sentences in listening and speaking.
Comprehension and collaboration
Comprehends and expands on oral language.
Participates in conversations with peers and adults about topics of interest.
Listens to others and takes turns speaking.
Asks questions to get information, seeks help, or clarifies something that is not understood.
Foundational Skills for Reading
Print Concepts
Holds book upright and identifies the front and back of a book.
Progresses in learning how to handle and care for books; knows how to view one page at a time in sequence from front to back; and understands that a book has a title, author, and illustrator.
Demonstrates increasing awareness of concepts of print, such as reading moves from top to bottom and from left to right, speech can be written down, and print conveys a message.
Develops an awareness of environmental print such as signs, letters, newspapers, lists, messages, and menus.
Knows that letters of the alphabet are a special category of visual graphics that can be individually named.
Recognizes and names letters such as those in his/her name, names of family and friends, and those seen in environmental print.
Recognizes words as units of print that are separated by spaces.
Phonological Awareness
Listens to and identifies sounds that are in the environment.
Shows growing ability to hear and discriminate separate syllables in words.
Progresses in recognizing matching sounds and rhymes in familiar words, games, songs, stories, and poems.
Shows growing awareness of beginning and ending sounds of words.
Word Recognition
Recognizes a word as a unit of print.
Recognize words such as his/her name, names of family and friends, and familiar environmental print.
Literature
Key Ideas and Details
Shows growing interest and involvement in listening to and discussing a variety of fiction and nonfiction books and poetry.
Looks through books independently and asks to have books read to them.
Recognizes story elements such as characters, sequence of events, and theme of a story.

Demonstrates progress in retelling and dictating stories from books and experiences; acts out stories in dramatic play; asks to take home books; goes to the library; and engages in pretend reading with other children.
Integration of Knowledge and Ideas
Engages in questioning, reflecting, and relating a story to personal experiences including use of new vocabulary.
Writing
Text Type and Purposes
Progresses from using scribble shapes or pictures to represent ideas, to using letter-like symbols or invented spelling, to copying or writing familiar words such as his/her own name.
Uses a combination of drawing, dictating, and writing to communicate ideas, thoughts, and feelings.
Demonstrates an understanding that writing relays a message that can be read.
Begins to use functional print in play.
Uses a variety of writing tools and materials, such as pencils, crayons and computers.
Begins to recognize that writing patterns progress from top to bottom, left to right, and words are separated by spaces.
Mathematics
Number – Counting and Cardinality
Number Names
Develops increased ability to counts in sequence to ten and beyond.
Begins to identify number symbols one to ten.
Counting To Tell the Number of Objects
Uses one-to-one correspondence in counting objects and matching groups of objects.
Matches quantity with number symbols.
Comparing and Ordering Numbers
Uses comparative words such as more, less, fewer, equal to.
Begins to recognize the order of numbers, e.g. before, after and between.
Number – Operations and the Problems they Solve
Composing and decomposing numbers; addition and subtraction
Develops increased ability to recognize addition as putting objects together and subtraction as taking objects apart.
Identifies parts in relationship to the whole.
Measurement and Data
Direct Measurement
Understand that objects have measurable attributes, such as length or weight. A single object might have several measurable attributes of interest.
Estimates the size of objects in comparison to a common unit of measurement, such as more/less, short/tall, long/short, big/little, and light/heavy.
Begins to construct a sense of time through participation in daily activities.
Representing and Interpreting Data
Classify objects according to common characteristics, such as color, size, or shape.
Begins to incorporate estimating and measuring activities into play.
Begins to recognize and interpret information presented in tables, graphs and symbols.
Geometry
Shapes, their attributes, and spatial reasoning
Recognizes, duplicates, and creates simple patterns using a variety of materials.

Progresses in ability to recognize terms of directionality, order, and positions of themselves and objects in their environment, such as up, down, over, under, top, bottom, inside, outside, in front, and behind.
Recognizes, describes, compares, and names common shapes.
Determines whether or not two shapes are the same size and shape.
Science
Science as Inquiry
Foundational Knowledge of Scientific Inquiry
Expresses wonder and asks questions about the world around them.
Observes and discusses similarities and differences among objects and materials, including cause and effect
Investigates and problem solves through active exploration of the environment.
Progresses in ability to describe and discuss predictions, explanations, and generalizations.
Utilization of Inquiry
Uses senses and a variety of tools to gather information, investigate materials, and observe processes and relationships
Collects, describes, and records information through a variety of means to lead to new understanding of the world around them.
Scientific Knowledge
Understanding the living and physical world
Observes and describes the immediate and familiar world, such as the natural world, materials, living things, and natural processes.
Shows increased awareness and beginning understanding of changes in materials and cause-effect relationships, such as recognize that materials can exist in several physical states.
Demonstrates expanding knowledge of and respect for the environment.
The Arts
Music and Movement
Self Expression
Participates in music activities, including listening, singing and finger plays.
Creates music through a variety of techniques.
Foundations of Music and Movement
Demonstrates an understanding of movement as it relates to music.
Uses a variety of instruments including non-traditional and natural objects.
Responds to and indentifies particular musical elements such as rhythm and style.
Visual Art
Self Expression
Progresses in ability to express emotion and communicates ideas through creative artwork.
Demonstrates growing ability to plan, work independently, and demonstrate care and persistence in a variety of art project.
Develops growing ability to create artwork that reflects an idea, theme, or story.
Foundations of Visual Arts
Explores color and texture using different mediums, including clay, natural materials, wood, paper, crayons, chalk, paint, glue, paste, etc.
Begins to demonstrate increased detail in a variety of artwork, including drawings, paintings, models, and other multi-dimensional artwork.
Dramatic Play
Self Expression
Participates in a variety of dramatic play activities throughout the day in a variety of settings that becomes more extended and complex.
Expresses ideas, feelings, and emotions through dramatic play.
Shows growing creativity and imagination in using materials and assuming roles, e.g. interaction with costume pieces, props, puppets, fabric, etc.
Tells and re-enacts stories and experiences through dramatic play.
Physical Health and Development
Fine Motor
Fine Motor Development
Demonstrates increased ability, strength, dexterity, and control to manipulate and use tools such as scissors, staplers, hammers, and fastening tools.
Demonstrates increased accuracy of eye-hand coordination and use of opposing hand movements to build with blocks, string beads, cut with scissors, or put together puzzles.
Progress in ability to use writing, drawing and art tools, including pencils, markers, chalk, paint brushes, and various types of technology.
Begins to demonstrate self help skills such as buttoning and zipping.
Gross Motor
Gross Motor Development
Demonstrates increased control and proficiency in walking, running, jumping, hopping, skipping, marching, and galloping.
Demonstrates increased abilities to coordinate movements in throwing, catching, kicking, bouncing balls, and ascending and descending stairs.
Moves with emergent balance on lines, balance beams, curbs, riding equipment, and play structures.
Health and Safety Practices
Healthy Development
Demonstrates ability to identify and make healthy food choices.
Participates actively in games, outdoor play and other forms of exercise that enhances physical fitness.
Exhibits increased physical growth, strength, stamina, endurance and flexibility.
Demonstrates growing independence in daily health routines and habits in hygiene, nutrition and personal care when eating, dressing, washing hands, brushing teeth, and toileting.
Demonstrates an understanding of the need for different apparel in different climates and weather conditions.
Safety Practices
Participates in safety games, songs and stories.
Recognizes symbols indicating danger.
Follows classroom and community safety rules, such as fire drills, traffic and pedestrian safety, and responding appropriately to potentially harmful objects, substances, and activities.
